SIMPLE: reward
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reward
<hw>Re*ward"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Rewarded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rewarding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>rewarder</ets>,
another form of <ets>regarder</ets>, of German origin. The original
sense is, to look at, regard, hence, to regard as worthy, give a reward
to. See <er>Ward</er>, <er>Regard</er>.]</ety> <def>To give in return,
whether good or evil; -- commonly in a good sense; to requite; to
recompense; to repay; to compensate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After the deed that is done, one doom shall <qex>reward</qex>,⟦br⟧
Mercy or no mercy as truth will accord.</q> <rj><qau>Piers
Plowman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou hast <qex>rewarded</qex> me good, whereas I have
<qex>rewarded</qex> thee evil.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam. xxiv.
17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will render vengeance to mine enemies, and will
<qex>reward</qex> them that hate me.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xxxii.
41.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God <qex>rewards</qex> those that have made use of the single
talent.</q> <rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reward</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Reward
<hw>Re*ward"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Reward</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>, and cf. <er>Regard</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Regard; respect; consideration.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take <qex>reward</qex> of thine own value.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is given in return for good or evil done
or received; esp., that which is offered or given in return for some
service or attainment, as for excellence in studies, for the return of
something lost, etc.; recompense; requital.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou returnest⟦br⟧
From flight, seditious angel, to receive⟦br⟧
Thy merited <qex>reward</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Rewards</qex> and punishments do always presuppose something
willingly done well or ill.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, the fruit of one's labor or works.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The dead know not anything, neither have they any more a
<qex>reward</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Eccl. ix. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Compensation or remuneration for
services; a sum of money paid or taken for doing, or forbearing to do,
some act.</def> <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Recompense; compensation; remuneration; pay;
requital; retribution; punishment.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rewardable</ent>⟦br⟧
